The derivative of inverse functions If $f$ is a one-to-one function with inverse function $f^{-1}$, and $f&rsquo;(f^{-1}(a))\ne 0$, then the inverse function is differentiable at $a$ and: $$ (f^{-1})&rsquo;(a)=\frac{1}{f&rsquo;(f^{-1}(a))} $$
Example Consider $f(x) = x^2$ on the restricted domain $[0, \infty)$.
Show that $f$ has an inverse and that domain. Find $(f^{-1})&rsquo;(1)$ using the above formula. Find $(f^{-1})&rsquo;(4)$ using the above formula. Find the inverse of $f$ and show that the computed derivatives match what we expect. Note that in 321 we define a function by a domain and a codomain. In that context, $f: A \to B$ is invertible if and only if $f$ is both one-to-one (injective) and $f$ is onto (surjective). In calculus we&rsquo;re just considering the case where $B=f(A)$ and so the functions that we are considering are by their very nature already surjective. That&rsquo;s why we only need to test injectivity.&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
